-- 
Dendreon, Eaton Vance, Esterline, Netflix: U.S. Equity Movers

-- B y   I n y o u n g   H w a n g   a n d   J e f f   K e a r n s
-- 
2011-09-02T20:22:03Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-01/esterline-technologies-finisar-h-r-block-netflix-u-s-equity-preview.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in U.S. trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses, and prices are as of 4 p.m. in New York.  Bank of America Corp. (BAC)   was the worst performer in
the Dow Jones Industrial Average, losing 8.3 percent to $7.25.
The largest U.S. lender,  JPMorgan Chase & Co. (JPM)   and
 Goldman Sachs Group Inc. (GS)   are among firms that may be
sued by the U.S. Federal Housing Finance Agency over faulty
mortgage loans, according to six people with knowledge of the
matter.  JPMorgan fell 4.6 percent to $34.63. Goldman Sachs slid 4.6
percent to $107.06.  Dendreon Corp. (DNDN)   fell 7.8 percent to $10.96, the
lowest price since Aug. 12. The drugmaker had its price estimate
cut to $14 from $20 by Robert W. Baird & Co. Oncologists said
they haven’t been reimbursed yet for the Seattle-based company’s
prostate cancer drug because of Medicare and regional carrier
issues, according to Baird’s note.  Eaton Vance Corp. (EV)   fell 7 percent, the most since
Aug. 8, to $22.27. The mutual fund manager was downgraded to
“Sell” from Neutral” at Ticonderoga Securities.  Esterline Technologies Corp. (ESL)   erased 13 percent,
the most since February 2009, to $64.16. The aerospace and
defense parts supplier forecast adjusted earnings in 2011 to be
no more than $4.55 a share, falling short of the average analyst
estimate of $5.07.  Finisar Corp. (FNSR)   rallied 8.7 percent to $20.21, the
highest price since July 26. The maker of fiber-optic
transmission gear forecast adjusted second-quarter earnings of
as much as 24 cents a share, topping the average analyst
estimate of 20 cents.  H&R Block Inc. (HRB)   lost 12 percent to $13.41, the
biggest decline in the  S&P 500 . The biggest U.S. tax preparer
reported first-quarter revenue was $267.6 million, missing the
average analyst estimate of $276.2 million.  Liz Claiborne Inc. (LIZ)   gained 9.1 percent to $5.52,
the highest price since Aug. 5. The owner of Juicy Couture and
Kate Spade said it agreed to sell its Mexx business to cut
losses from the unit and meet targets. Liz Claiborne will sell
Mexx to a joint venture with The Gores Group LLC in exchange for
18.75 percent of the common equity of the venture and $85
million in cash, the New York-based company said in a statement
today.  Netflix Inc. (NFLX)   slumped 8.6 percent, the second-
biggest drop in the S&P 500, to $213.11. Starz LLC, the premium
cable channel controlled by billionaire John Malone’s Liberty
Media Corp., said it ended contract renewal talks with the
company after failing to come to terms for films online.  Peabody Energy Corp. (BTU)   fell 3.9 percent to $45.79
for its biggest decline since Aug. 18. The largest U.S. coal
producer said a roof fall that stopped production at its North
Goonyella coking coal mine in Australia may cut third-quarter
earnings by as much as $125 million.  To contact the reporters on this story:
